hip-gets-rebranded-ahead-of-2020-season|title=FR Americas Championship Gets Rebranded Ahead of 2020 Season|website=FR Americas Championship|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n== Teams and drivers ==\nRelentless Motorsports will be the first Canadian-based team to compete in the series.<ref name=\"Relentless\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013294-first-canadian-based-team-enters-f3-americas-for-2020|title=First Canadian-Based Team Enters F3 Americas for 2020|website=F3 Americas Championship|date=20 December 2019}}</ref>  All drivers compete with [[Honda in motorsport|Honda]]-powered [[Ligier]] JS F3 cars on [[Hankook Tire|Hankook]] tires.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n!Team\n!{{Tooltip|No.|Car number}}\n!Driver\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Crosslink/Kiwi Motorsport\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Joshua Car]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013068-f4-u-s-champion-joshua-car-confirms-2020-f3-americas-campaign|title=F4 U.S. Champion Joshua Car Confirms 2020 F3 Americas Campaign|website=F3 Americas Championship|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|USA}} Momentum Motorsports\n| 16\n|{{Flagicon|USA}} Kent Vaccaro<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013559-momentum-motorsports-inks-kent-vaccaro-to-fr-americas-championship-program-for-2020|title=Momentum Motorsports Inks Kent Vaccaro to FR Americas Championship Program for 2020|website=FR Americas Championship|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Wulff Motorsports<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013435-wulff-motorsports-launches-f3-americas-program|title=Wulff Motorsports Launches F3 Americas Program|website=F3 Americas Championship|date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n| 61\n| {{flagicon|}} TBA\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Jensen Global Advisors\n| 99\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Logan Cusson<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013542-cusson-returns-to-fr-americas-with-jensen-for-sophomore-season|title=Cusson Returns to FR Americas With Jensen Global Advisors for Sophomore Season |date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Alliance Racing Sponsored by<br>[[Richard Rawlings|Gas Monkey Energy Drink]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013426-alliance-racing-and-gas-monkey-energy-level-up-to-f3-in-2020|title=Alliance Racing and Gas Monkey Energy Level Up to F3 in 2020|website=F3 Americas Championship|date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|}} TBA\n|-\n|rowspan=2| {{flagicon|USA}} Global Racing Group\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Dario Cangialosi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013604-formula-race-promotions-star-dario-cangialosi-confirms-fr-americas-ride|title=Formula Race Promotions Star Dario Cangialosi Confirms FR Americas Ride|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Linus Lundqvist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013579-linus-lundqvist-targets-formula-regional-americas-championship-title-run|title=Linus Lundqvist Targets Formula Regional Americas Championship Title Run|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Newman Wachs Racing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013441-newman-wachs-racing-expands-to-the-f3-americas-championship|title=NEWMAN WACHS RACING EXPANDS TO THE F3 AMERICAS CHAMPIONSHIP|date=February 10, 2020|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Jordan Missig<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013551-jordan-missig-joins-newman-wachs-racing-for-2020-season|title=Jordan Missig Joins Newman Wachs Racing for 2020 Season|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|}} TBA\n|-\n|rowspan=2| {{flagicon|CAN}} Relentless Motorsports\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Andrew Dobbie<ref name=\"Relentless\"/>\n|-\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Mitch Egner<ref name=\"Relentless\"/>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Velocity Racing Development\n| TBA\n| {{flagicon|COL}} Mathias Soler-Obel<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racetechdevelopmentgroup.com/media/mathias-soler-obel-rejoins-velocity-racing-development-for-sophomore-f3-americas-season/|title=MATHIAS SOLER-OBEL REJOINS VELOCITY RACING DEVELOPMENT FOR SOPHOMORE F3 AMERICAS SEASON|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Race calendar ==\nThe series schedule was announced on 19 December 2019.  The final round is set to be held in support of the [[2020 United States Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2013289-2020-f3-americas-schedule-revealed|title=2020 F3 Americas Schedule Revealed|work=F3 Americas Championship|date=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.framericas.com/events|title=Formula Regional Americas Championship 2020 Schedule|work=F3 Americas Championship|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, the season opening round in Atlanta was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013530-scca-pro-racing-postpones-the-start-of-the-season|title=SCCA Pro Racing Postpones the Start of the Season|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>  [[Circuit Trois-Rivi\u00e8res]] in Quebec, Canada was scheduled to be the first international event for the series, but was canceled on 16 April 2020 due to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f3americas.com/articles/2012868-f3-americas-championship-makes-international-debut-on-the-streets-of-quebec-in-2020|title=F3 AMERICAS CHAMPIONSHIP MAKES INTERNATIONAL DEBUT ON THE STREETS OF QUEBEC IN 2020|website=F3 Americas Championship|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.framericas.com/articles/2013620-grand-prix-de-trois-rivieres-update|title=Grand Prix de Trois-Rivi\u00e8res Update|website=F3 Americas Championship|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n! colspan=2| Round\n! Circuit\n! Date\n<!--! Pole Position\n! Fastest Lap\n! Winning Driver\n! Winning Team-->\n! Supporting\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 1\n! R1\n|rowspan=3| [[Circuit of the Americas]], [[Austin, Texas|Austin]]\n|rowspan=3| 5\u20137 June\n|rowspan=3| ''[[2020 Formula 4 United States Championship|Formula 4 United States Championship]]''\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n! R3\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 2\n! R1\n|rowspan=3| [[Virginia International Raceway]], [[Alton, Virginia|Alton]]\n|rowspan=3| 17\u201319 July\n|rowspan=3| ''[[2020 Formula 4 United States Championship|Formula 4 United States Championship]]''<br>''Formula Race Promotions''\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n! R3\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 3\n! R1\n|rowspan=3| [[Barber Motorsports Park]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]\n|rowspan=3| 31 July\u20132 August\n|rowspan=3| ''[[2020 Formula 4 United States Championship|Formula 4 United States Championship]]''<br>''Radical Cup''\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n! R3\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 4\n! R1\n|rowspan=3| [[Sebring International Raceway]], [[Sebring, Florida|Sebring]]\n|rowspan=3| 25\u201327 September\n|rowspan=3| ''[[2020 Formula 4 United States Championship|Formula 4 United States Championship]]''\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n! R3\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 5\n! R1\n|rowspan=2| [[Circuit of the Americas]], [[Austin, Texas|Austin]]\n|rowspan=2| 23\u201325 October\n|rowspan=2| ''[[2020 Formula One World Championship|Formula One]]''<br>''[[2020 Formula 4 United States Championship|Formula 4 United States Championship]]''<br>''[[2020 W Series|W Series]]''\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n!rowspan=3| TBD\n! R1\n|rowspan=3| [[Road Atlanta]], [[Braselton, Georgia|Braselton]]\n|rowspan=3| TBD\n|rowspan=3|\n|-\n! R2\n|-\n! R3\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official Website|https://www.framericas.com/}}\n\n[[Category:FIA Formula 3 Championship seasons]]\n[[Category:2020 in American motorsport|Formula Regional Americas Championship]]\n[[Category:2020 in Formula 3|Formula Regional Americas Championship]]\n[[Category:Scheduled motorsport seasons|Formula Regional Americas Championship]]\n", "name_user": "Mcbjmund", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRace calendar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Formula_Regional_Americas_Championship"}
{"title_page": "KOUA", "text_new": "\n\nKOUA is a [[London]] based fashion brand founded in 2014 by [[Erika Alvarez|Erika Alvarez]].\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = KOUA\n| founder             = Erika Alvarez\n| founding_location   = London\n| headquarters        = 20-22 Wenlock Road, London, N1 7GU\n| origins             = Mexico\n| website             = https://kouamexico.uk\n}}\n\n== Overview ==\nKOUA, also stylized KOUA Mexico, is a contemporary fashion brand that aims to promote [[Mexico|Mexican]] arts and crafts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kouamexico.uk/|title=KOUA Mexico|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> They work with [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico]] to create fairtrade, ethically-sourced products, to preserve traditional Mexican embroidery and textiles, and to preserve the ancestral identity of Mexico's indigenous communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://missportmanteau.com/interview-koua-mexzik/|title=INTERVIEW: Erika Alvarez of Koua|last=|first=|date=3 April 2017|website=Miss Portmanteau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kouamexico.uk/koua-responsibility/|title=KOUA Responsibility|last=|first=|date=2016|website=KOUA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://born.com/brand/QnJhbmQ6NDY5|title=Koua Mexico|last=|first=|date=|website=BORN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nErika Alvarez, KOUA's founder, CEO and creative director, was born in Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gcu.ac.uk/alumni/profile/gculondon/erikaalvarez/|title=Erika Alvarez|last=|first=|date=|website=GCU Glasgow Caledonian University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> She is also a fashion influencer and was 2018 winner of [[GCU London]] Alumna of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gculondon.ac.uk/aboutus/alumni/alumnusoftheyearaward/2018winner/|title=2018 Winner|last=|first=|date=2018|website=GCU London|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yJN-OAcJDpk|title=GCU London presents Erika Alvares with Alumna of the Year|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Youtube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><br />\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "\n\nKOUA is a [[London]] based fashion brand founded in 2014 by [[Erika alvarez|Erika Alvarez]].\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = KOUA\n| founder             = Erika Alvarez\n| founding_location   = London\n| headquarters        = 20-22 Wenlock Road, London, N1 7GU\n| origins             = Mexico\n| website             = https://kouamexico.uk\n}}\n\n== Overview ==\nKOUA, also stylized KOUA Mexico, is a contemporary fashion brand that aims to promote [[Mexico|Mexican]] arts and crafts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kouamexico.uk/|title=KOUA Mexico|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> They work with [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico]] to create fairtrade, ethically-sourced products, to preserve traditional Mexican embroidery and textiles, and to preserve the ancestral identity of Mexico's indigenous communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://missportmanteau.com/interview-koua-mexzik/|title=INTERVIEW: Erika Alvarez of Koua|last=|first=|date=3 April 2017|website=Miss Portmanteau|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kouamexico.uk/koua-responsibility/|title=KOUA Responsibility|last=|first=|date=2016|website=KOUA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://born.com/brand/QnJhbmQ6NDY5|title=Koua Mexico|last=|first=|date=|website=BORN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nErika Alvarez, KOUA's founder, CEO and creative director, was born in Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gcu.ac.uk/alumni/profile/gculondon/erikaalvarez/|title=Erika Alvarez|last=|first=|date=|website=GCU Glasgow Caledonian University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> She is also a fashion influencer and was 2018 winner of [[GCU London]] Alumna of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gculondon.ac.uk/aboutus/alumni/alumnusoftheyearaward/2018winner/|title=2018 Winner|last=|first=|date=2018|website=GCU London|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yJN-OAcJDpk|title=GCU London presents Erika Alvares with Alumna of the Year|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Youtube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><br />\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "RMJ13", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KOUA"}
{"title_page": "Aphrodisiac", "text_new": "{{short description|Chemical agents or odorants that stimulate sexual desires}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\nAn '''aphrodisiac''' is a substance that increases sexual desire, sexual pleasure, or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Melnyk|first=John P.|last2=Marcone|first2=Massimo F.|date=May 2011|title=Aphrodisiacs from plant and animal sources\u2014A review of current scientific literature|journal=Food Research International|volume=44|issue=4|pages=840\u2013850|doi=10.1016/j.foodres.2011.02.043}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The psychology of human sexuality|last=Lehmiller, Justin J.|isbn=9781119164708|edition=Second|location=Hoboken, NJ|oclc=992580729|date = 12 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Sandroni|first=Paola|date=October 2001|title=Aphrodisiacs past and present: A historical review|journal=Clinical Autonomic Research|volume=11|issue=5|pages=303\u2013307|doi=10.1007/bf02332975|issn=0959-9851}}</ref> Substances range from a variety of plants, spices, foods, and synthetic chemicals.<ref name=\":0\" /> Therefore, they can be classified by their chemical properties (i.e., substances that are natural and unnatural).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Bella|first=Anthony J|last2=Shamloul|first2=Rany|date=June 2014|title=Traditional Plant Aphrodisiacs and Male Sexual Dysfunction: PLANT APHRODISIACS|journal=Phytotherapy Research|volume=28|issue=6|pages=831\u2013835|doi=10.1002/ptr.5074}}</ref> Natural aphrodisiacs like [[alcohol]] are further classified into plant-based and non-plant-based substances.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Shamloul|first=Rany|date=January 2010|title=Natural Aphrodisiacs|journal=The Journal of Sexual Medicine|volume=7|issue=1|pages=39\u201349|doi=10.1111/j.1743-6109.2009.01521.x|pmid=19796015}}</ref> Unnatural aphrodisiacs like [[Ecstasy (drug)|Ecstasy]] are classified as those that are manufactured to imitate a natural substance.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Aphrodisiacs can also be classified by their type of effects (i.e., psychological or physiological).<ref name=\":0\" /> Aphrodisiacs that contain hallucinogenic properties like [[Bufo|Bufo toad]] have psychological effects on a person that can increase sexual desire and sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Aphrodisiacs that contain smooth muscle relaxing properties like [[yohimbine]] have physiological effects on a person that can affect hormone levels and increase blood flow.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nIt is important to note that substances which only affect a person's behavior are susceptible to the [[Placebo|placebo effect]].<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Placebo|Placebo effects]] are defined as strong beliefs that manifest themselves and therefore are misconstrued to confirm a false positive.<ref name=\":1\" /> It is commonplace to see the placebo effect in the debate on why aphrodisiacs work; those that argue for the placebo effect say that individuals want to believe in the effectiveness of the substance.<ref name=\":1\" /> Other substances that impede on areas that aphrodisiacs aim to enhance are classified as [[anaphrodisiac]]s.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBoth males and females can benefit from the use of aphrodisiacs, but they are more focused on males as their properties tend to increase testosterone levels rather than estrogen levels.<ref name=\":2\" /> This is in part due to the historical context of aphrodisiacs, which focused solely on males. Only recent attention has been paid to understanding how aphrodisiacs can aide female sexual function.<ref name=\":4\" /> In addition, cultural influence in appropriate sexual behavior from male and females also play a part in the research gap.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==History==\nThe name comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u1f00\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd, ''aphrodisiakon'', i.e. \"sexual, aphrodisiac\", from ''aphrodisios'', i.e. \"pertaining to [[Aphrodite]]\",<ref>{{LSJ|*)afrodisiako/s|\u1f00\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd|ref}}.</ref><ref>{{cite dictionary|title=Aphrodisiac|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=aphrodisiac&allowed_in_frame=0|dictionary=[[Online Etymology Dictionary]]}}</ref> the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Twelve Olympians|goddess]] of love. Throughout human history, food, drinks, and behaviors have had a reputation for making sex more attainable and/or pleasurable. However, from a historical and scientific standpoint, the alleged results may have been mainly due to mere belief by their users that they would be effective ([[placebo effect]]). Likewise, many medicines are reported to ''affect'' libido in inconsistent or idiopathic ways:<ref name=\"West15\">{{cite journal |vauthors=West E, Krychman M |title=Natural Aphrodisiacs-A Review of Selected Sexual Enhancers |journal=Sex Med Rev |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=279\u2013288 |date=October 2015 |pmid=27784600 |doi=10.1002/smrj.62 |url=}}</ref> enhancing or diminishing overall sexual desire depending on the situation of the subject. For example, Bupropion ([[Bupropion|Wellbutrin]]) is known as an [[antidepressant]] that can counteract other co-prescribed antidepressants having libido-diminishing effects. However, because Wellbutrin only increases the libido in the special case that it is already impaired by related medications, it is not generally classed as an aphrodisiac.\n\nAncient civilizations like Chinese, Indian, Egyptian, Roman, and Greek cultures believed that certain substances could provide the key to improving sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This was important because some men suffered from erectile dysfunction and could not reproduce.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Men who were unable to have large families or who were unable to impregnate their wives were seen as a failure, whereas men who were able to conceive and therefore have large families were respected causing a great need for a solution.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Others who did not suffer from this desired performance enhancers.<ref name=\":3\" /> Regardless of their usage, these substances gained popularity and began to be documented with information being passed down generations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Hindu cultures wrote poems dated back around 2000 to 1000 BC that spoke of performance enhancers, ingredients, and usage tips.<ref name=\":2\" /> Chinese cultures wrote text dated back to 2697 to 2595 BC.<ref name=\":4\" /> Roman and Chinese cultures documented their belief in aphrodisiac qualities in animal genitalia while Egyptian wrote tips for treating erectile dysfunction.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[Ambrisentan|Ambrien]], [[Bufo|Bufo toad]], [[yohimbine]], [[Epimedium|horny goat weed]], [[ginseng]], [[alcohol]], and food are recorded throughout these texts as containing aphrodisiac qualities.<ref name=\":0\" /> While numerous plants, [[extract]]s or manufactured hormones have been proposed as aphrodisiacs, there is little high-quality [[evidence-based medicine|clinical evidence]] for the efficacy or long-term safety of using them.<ref name=\"West15\" /><ref name=\"drugs\">{{cite web|title=Sexual health|url=https://www.drugs.com/sexual-health.html|publisher=Drugs.com|accessdate=17 May 2018|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Types==\n\n=== Ambrien ===\n[[File:Ambergris.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Ambergris]]\n\n[[Ambrien]] is found in the gut of sperm whales.<ref name=\":2\" /> It is commonly used in Arab cultures as relief medication for headaches or as a performance enhancer.<ref name=\":2\" /> The chemical structure of Ambrien has shown to increase testosterone levels triggering sexual desire and sexual behavior in animal studies only.<ref name=\":2\" /> Further research is needed to know the effects on humans.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Bufo toad ===\n\n[[Bufo toad]] is found in the skin and glands of Bufo toads.<ref name=\":2\" /> It is commonly used in West Indian and Chinese cultures.<ref name=\":2\" /> West Indian cultures use it as an aphrodisiac called \u2018Love Stone\u2019.<ref name=\":2\" /> Chinese cultures use Bufo toad as heart medication called ''Chan su''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Research shows that it can have a negative effect on heart rate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Yohimbine ===\n[[File:Yohimbine structure.svg|thumb|upright=0.75|Yohimbine chemical structure]]\n\nYohimbine is a substance found in the bark of yohim trees in West Africa and, therefore, plant-based.<ref name=\":3\" /> It was traditionally used in West African cultures, in which the bark would be boiled and the resulting water drunk until its effects showed proven benefits in increasing sexual desire.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is now approved by the Food and Drug Administration and can be prescribed for sexual dysfunction in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> It is also found in over-the-counter health products.<ref name=\":0\" /> The chemical structure of yohimbine is an indole alkaloid that contains an adrenergic receptor blocker.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This blocker affects the central nervous system, autonomic nervous system, and penile tissue and vascular smooth muscle cells that help men with physiological issues and treats psychogenic erectile dysfunction.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Known side effects include nausea, anxiety, irregular heartbeats, and restlessness.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Horny goat weed  ===\n\n[[Horny goat weed]] (''Epimedii herba'') is found in a group of flowering plants used in Chinese folk medicine.<ref name=\":0\" /> Its intended use was to treat medical conditions and improve sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\" /> The chemical structure of horny goat weed consists of icariin, a flavanol glycoside.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Icariin has been shown to improve hormone regulation along with other benefits.<ref name=\":0\" /> Animal studies show a positive correlation to aphrodisiac qualities, but further research is needed to know the effects on humans.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Alcohol and marijuana===\n{{See also|Cannabis and sex}}\n[[File:Alcohol.png|upright=0.75|thumb|right|Alcohol Molecule]]\n\n[[Alcohol]] has been associated as an aphrodisiac due to its effect as a central nervous system depressant.<ref name=\":4\" /> Depressants can increase sexual desire and sexual behavior through disinhibition.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Alcohol affects people both physiologically and psychologically, and is therefore difficult to determine exactly how people are experiencing its aphrodisiacal effects (i.e., aphrodisiac qualities or the expectancy effect).<ref name=\":1\" /> Alcohol taken in moderate quantities can elicit a positive increase in sexual desire whereas larger quantities are associated with difficulties reaching sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chronic alcohol consumption is related to sexual dysfunction.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Marijuana]] reports are mixed with half of users claiming an increase in sexual desire and sexual pleasure while the other half reports no effect.<ref name=\":1\" /> Marijuana strain, consumption, and individual sensitivity&nbsp;are known factors that affect results.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Food ===\n[[File:Insam (ginseng).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Ginseng]]\nMany cultures have turned to food as a source of increasing sexual desire; however, significant research is lacking in the study of aphrodisiac qualities in food <ref name=\":1\" />. Most claims can be linked to the placebo effect aforementioned <ref name=\":1\" />. Misconceptions revolve around the visual appearance of these foods in relation to male and female genitalia (i.e., carrots, bananas, oysters, and the like) <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. Other beliefs arise from the thought of consuming animal genitals and absorbing their properties (i.e., cow cod soup in Jamaica or Ballut in the Philippines) <ref name=\":0\" />. The story of Aphrodite, who was born from the sea, is another reason why individuals believe seafood is another source of aphrodisiacs <ref name=\":4\" />. Foods that contain volatile oils have gained little recognition in their ability to improve sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior because they are irritants when released through the urinary tract <ref name=\":2\" />. Chocolate has been reported to increase sexual desire in women who consume it over those who do not <ref name=\":0\" />. Cloves and sage have been reported to demonstrate aphrodisiac qualities but their effects are\u00a0not yet specified <ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==== Ginseng ====\n\n[[Ginseng]] is found in Korea and is grouped in the Panaz family, known as Chinese ginseng.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The chemical structure of ginseng consists of ginsenosides and saponin glycosides.<ref name=\":3\" /> There are three different ways to process ginseng.<ref name=\":3\" /> Fresh ginseng is cut at four years of growth, white ginseng is cut at four to six years of growth, and red ginseng is cut, dried, and steamed at six years of growth.<ref name=\":3\" />&nbsp; Red ginseng has been reported to be the most effective aphrodisiac of the three.<ref name=\":3\" /> Known side effects include mild gastrointestinal upset.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Synthetic ===\n{{See also|Sex and drugs}}\n[[File:MDMA (simple).svg|upright=0.75|thumb|right|Ecstasy Molecule]] \nPopular party substances have been reported by users to consist of aphrodisiac properties because of their enhancing effects with sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n[[Ecstasy (drug)|Ecstasy]] users have reported an increase in sexual desire and sexual pleasure; however, there have been reports of delays in orgasm in both sexes and erectile difficulties in men.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Poppers]], an inhalant, have been linked to increased sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Known side effects are headaches, nausea, and temporary erectile difficulties.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Phenethylamines ====\n\n[[Amphetamine]] and [[methamphetamine]] are [[substituted phenethylamine|phenethylamine derivatives]] which are known to increase libido and cause frequent or prolonged erections as potential side effects, particularly at high [[wikt:supratherapeutic|supratherapeutic]] doses where sexual hyperexcitability and hypersexuality can occur;<ref name=\"Human amph effects\">{{cite book | author=Gunne LM | title=Drug Addiction II: Amphetamine, Psychotogen, and Marihuana Dependence | date=2013 | publisher=Springer | location=Berlin, Germany; Heidelberg, Germany | isbn=9783642667091 | pages=247\u2013260 | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gb_uCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA247#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate=4 December 2015 | chapter=Effects of Amphetamines in Humans }}</ref><ref name=\"FDA Effects\">{{cite web | title = Adderall XR Prescribing Information | url = http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2013/021303s026lbl.pdf | pages = 4&ndash;8 | work = United States Food and Drug Administration |date=December 2013 | accessdate = 30 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Libido\">{{cite journal | author = Montgomery KA | title = Sexual desire disorders | journal = Psychiatry (Edgmont) | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = 50&ndash;55 |date=June 2008 | pmid = 19727285 | pmc = 2695750 | doi = }}</ref><ref name=\"Desoxyn\">{{cite web| title=Desoxyn Prescribing Information| url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2013/005378s028lbl.pdf|date=December 2013 |work=United States Food and Drug Administration| accessdate=6 January 2014 | quote = ADVERSE REACTIONS&nbsp;... '''changes in libido'''; frequent or prolonged erections. [emphasis added]}}</ref> however, in some individuals who use these drugs, libido is reduced.<ref name=\"FDA Effects\" /><ref name=\"Desoxyn\" />\n\n==== Testosterone ====\n[[Libido]] in males is linked to levels of sex hormones, particularly [[testosterone]].<ref name=drugs/><ref>{{cite journal |title=The effects of testosterone on the cavernous tissue and erectile function |author=R. Shabsigh| year=1997|journal=World J. Urol.| pmid=9066090 | volume = 15 | pages = 21\u20136 | doi = 10.1007/BF01275152 |issue=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fisher|first=Helen E.|last2=Aron|first2=Arthur|last3=Brown|first3=Lucy L.|date=2006-12-29|title=Romantic love: a mammalian brain system for mate choice|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=361|issue=1476|pages=2173\u20132186|doi=10.1098/rstb.2006.1938|issn=0962-8436|pmid=17118931|pmc=1764845}}</ref> When a reduced sex drive occurs in individuals with relatively low levels of testosterone, particularly in [[postmenopausal]] women or men over age 60,<ref name=\"snyder\">{{cite journal|pmc=5209754|year=2016|last1=Snyder|first1=P. J|title=Effects of Testosterone Treatment in Older Men|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=374|issue=7|pages=611\u2013624|last2=Bhasin|first2=S|last3=Cunningham|first3=G. R|last4=Matsumoto|first4=A. M|last5=Stephens-Shields|first5=A. J|last6=Cauley|first6=J. A|last7=Gill|first7=T. M|last8=Barrett-Connor|first8=E|last9=Swerdloff|first9=R. S|last10=Wang|first10=C|last11=Ensrud|first11=K. E|last12=Lewis|first12=C. E|last13=Farrar|first13=J. T|last14=Cella|first14=D|last15=Rosen|first15=R. C|last16=Pahor|first16=M|last17=Crandall|first17=J. P|last18=Molitch|first18=M. E|last19=Cifelli|first19=D|last20=Dougar|first20=D|last21=Fluharty|first21=L|last22=Resnick|first22=S. M|last23=Storer|first23=T. W|last24=Anton|first24=S|last25=Basaria|first25=S|last26=Diem|first26=S. J|last27=Hou|first27=X|last28=Mohler Er|first28=I. I. I|last29=Parsons|first29=J. K|last30=Wenger|first30=N. K|display-authors=29|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1506119|pmid=26886521}}</ref> [[dietary supplement]]s that are purported to increase [[blood serum|serum]] testosterone concentrations have been used with intent to increase libido, although with limited benefit.<ref name=drugs/><ref name=snyder/> Long-term therapy with synthetic oral testosterone is associated with increased risk of [[cardiovascular diseases]].<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=4245724|year=2014|last1=Borst|first1=S. E|title=Cardiovascular risks and elevation of serum DHT vary by route of testosterone administration: A systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMC Medicine|volume=12|pages=211|last2=Shuster|first2=J. J|last3=Zou|first3=B|last4=Ye|first4=F|last5=Jia|first5=H|last6=Wokhlu|first6=A|last7=Yarrow|first7=J. F|doi=10.1186/s12916-014-0211-5|pmid=25428524}}</ref>\n\n== Risks ==\nSolid evidence is hard to obtain as these substances come from many different environments cross-culturally and therefore affect results due to variations in its growth and extraction.<ref name=\":3\" /> The same is also true for unnatural substances as variations in consumption and individual sensitivity can affect results.<ref name=\":1\" /> Folk medicine and self-prescribed methods can be potentially harmful as side effects are not fully known and therefore are not made aware to the people searching this topic on the internet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Popular culture==\n[[File:1926WantQuickPep.jpg|thumb|right|230px|An advertisement for pills from 1926 implies an aphrodisiac effect: \"full of red-blooded vim and push\".]]\n\nThe invention of an aphrodisiac is the basis of a number of films including [[Perfume: The Story of a Murderer (film)|''Perfume: The Story of a Murderer'']], ''[[Spanish Fly (1975 film)|Spanish Fly]]'', ''[[She'll Follow You Anywhere]]'', ''[[Love Potion No. 9 (film)|Love Potion No. 9]]'' and ''[[A Serbian Film]]''.  The first segment of [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask) (film)|Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask)]]'' is called \"Do Aphrodisiacs Work?\", and casts Allen as a [[court jester]] trying to seduce the [[Queen regnant|queen]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Anaphrodisiac]]\n* [[Food and sexuality]]\n* ''[[Fork Me, Spoon Me]]'', 2006 book\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Gabriele Frob\u00f6se, Rolf Frob\u00f6se, Michael Gross (Translator): ''Lust and Love: Is it more than Chemistry?'' Royal Society of Chemistry, 2006; {{ISBN|0-85404-867-7}}.\n* Michael Scott: \"Pillow Talk: A Comprehensive Guide to Erotic Hypnosis and Relyfe Programming\" Blue Deck Press, 2011; {{ISBN|0-98341-640-0}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aphrodisiacs}}\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/27752 ''Aphrodisiacs and Anti-aphrodisiacs: Three Essays on the Powers of Reproduction'' by John Davenport].\n\n{{-}}\n{{Aphrodisiacs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Aphrodisiacs| ]]\n[[Category:Sex and drugs]]\n[[Category:Drug classes defined by psychological effects]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chemical agents or odorants that stimulate sexual desires}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\nAn '''aphrodisiac''' is a substance that increases sexual desire, sexual pleasure, or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Melnyk|first=John P.|last2=Marcone|first2=Massimo F.|date=May 2011|title=Aphrodisiacs from plant and animal sources\u2014A review of current scientific literature|journal=Food Research International|volume=44|issue=4|pages=840\u2013850|doi=10.1016/j.foodres.2011.02.043}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The psychology of human sexuality|last=Lehmiller, Justin J.|isbn=9781119164708|edition=Second|location=Hoboken, NJ|oclc=992580729|date = 12 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Sandroni|first=Paola|date=October 2001|title=Aphrodisiacs past and present: A historical review|journal=Clinical Autonomic Research|volume=11|issue=5|pages=303\u2013307|doi=10.1007/bf02332975|issn=0959-9851}}</ref> Substances range from a variety of plants, spices, foods, and synthetic chemicals.<ref name=\":0\" /> Therefore, they can be classified by their chemical properties (i.e., substances that are natural and unnatural).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Bella|first=Anthony J|last2=Shamloul|first2=Rany|date=June 2014|title=Traditional Plant Aphrodisiacs and Male Sexual Dysfunction: PLANT APHRODISIACS|journal=Phytotherapy Research|volume=28|issue=6|pages=831\u2013835|doi=10.1002/ptr.5074}}</ref> Natural aphrodisiacs like [[alcohol]] are further classified into plant-based and non-plant-based substances.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Shamloul|first=Rany|date=January 2010|title=Natural Aphrodisiacs|journal=The Journal of Sexual Medicine|volume=7|issue=1|pages=39\u201349|doi=10.1111/j.1743-6109.2009.01521.x|pmid=19796015}}</ref> Unnatural aphrodisiacs like [[Ecstasy (drug)|Ecstasy]] are classified as those that are manufactured to imitate a natural substance.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Aphrodisiacs can also be classified by their type of effects (i.e., psychological or physiological).<ref name=\":0\" /> Aphrodisiacs that contain hallucinogenic properties like [[Bufo|Bufo toad]] have psychological effects on a person that can increase sexual desire and sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Aphrodisiacs that contain smooth muscle relaxing properties like [[yohimbine]] have physiological effects on a person that can affect hormone levels and increase blood flow.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nIt is important to note that substances which only affect a person's behavior are susceptible to the [[Placebo|placebo effect]].<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Placebo|Placebo effects]] are defined as strong beliefs that manifest themselves and therefore are misconstrued to confirm a false positive.<ref name=\":1\" /> It is commonplace to see the placebo effect in the debate on why aphrodisiacs work; those that argue for the placebo effect say that individuals want to believe in the effectiveness of the substance.<ref name=\":1\" /> Other substances that impede on areas that aphrodisiacs aim to enhance are classified as [[anaphrodisiac]]s.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBoth males and females can benefit from the use of aphrodisiacs, but they are more focused on males as their properties tend to increase testosterone levels rather than estrogen levels.<ref name=\":2\" /> This is in part due to the historical context of aphrodisiacs, which focused solely on males. Only recent attention has been paid to understanding how aphrodisiacs can aide female sexual function.<ref name=\":4\" /> In addition, cultural influence in appropriate sexual behavior from male and females also play a part in the research gap.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==History==\nThe name comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u1f00\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd, ''aphrodisiakon'', i.e. \"sexual, aphrodisiac\", from ''aphrodisios'', i.e. \"pertaining to [[Aphrodite]]\",<ref>{{LSJ|*)afrodisiako/s|\u1f00\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd|ref}}.</ref><ref>{{cite dictionary|title=Aphrodisiac|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=aphrodisiac&allowed_in_frame=0|dictionary=[[Online Etymology Dictionary]]}}</ref> the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Twelve Olympians|goddess]] of love. Throughout human history, food, drinks, and behaviors have had a reputation for making sex more attainable and/or pleasurable. However, from a historical and scientific standpoint, the alleged results may have been mainly due to mere belief by their users that they would be effective ([[placebo effect]]). Likewise, many medicines are reported to ''affect'' libido in inconsistent or idiopathic ways:<ref name=\"West15\">{{cite journal |vauthors=West E, Krychman M |title=Natural Aphrodisiacs-A Review of Selected Sexual Enhancers |journal=Sex Med Rev |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=279\u2013288 |date=October 2015 |pmid=27784600 |doi=10.1002/smrj.62 |url=}}</ref> enhancing or diminishing overall sexual desire depending on the situation of the subject. For example, Bupropion ([[Bupropion|Wellbutrin]]) is known as an [[antidepressant]] that can counteract other co-prescribed antidepressants having libido-diminishing effects. However, because Wellbutrin only increases the libido in the special case that it is already impaired by related medications, it is not generally classed as an aphrodisiac.\n\nAncient civilizations like Chinese, Indian, Egyptian, Roman, and Greek cultures believed that certain substances could provide the key to improving sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This was important because some men suffered from erectile dysfunction and could not reproduce.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Men who were unable to have large families or who were unable to impregnate their wives were seen as a failure, whereas men who were able to conceive and therefore have large families were respected causing a great need for a solution.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Others who did not suffer from this desired performance enhancers.<ref name=\":3\" /> Regardless of their usage, these substances gained popularity and began to be documented with information being passed down generations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Hindu cultures wrote poems dated back around 2000 to 1000 BC that spoke of performance enhancers, ingredients, and usage tips.<ref name=\":2\" /> Chinese cultures wrote text dated back to 2697 to 2595 BC.<ref name=\":4\" /> Roman and Chinese cultures documented their belief in aphrodisiac qualities in animal genitalia while Egyptian wrote tips for treating erectile dysfunction.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[Ambrisentan|Ambrien]], [[Bufo|Bufo toad]], [[yohimbine]], [[Epimedium|horny goat weed]], [[ginseng]], [[alcohol]], and food are recorded throughout these texts as containing aphrodisiac qualities.<ref name=\":0\" /> While numerous plants, [[extract]]s or manufactured hormones have been proposed as aphrodisiacs, there is little high-quality [[evidence-based medicine|clinical evidence]] for the efficacy or long-term safety of using them.<ref name=\"West15\" /><ref name=\"drugs\">{{cite web|title=Sexual health|url=https://www.drugs.com/sexual-health.html|publisher=Drugs.com|accessdate=17 May 2018|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Types==\n\n=== Ambrien ===\n[[File:Ambergris.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Ambergris]]\n\n[[Ambrien]] is found in the gut of sperm whales.<ref name=\":2\" /> It is commonly used in Arab cultures as relief medication for headaches or as a performance enhancer.<ref name=\":2\" /> The chemical structure of Ambrien has shown to increase testosterone levels triggering sexual desire and sexual behavior in animal studies only.<ref name=\":2\" /> Further research is needed to know the effects on humans.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Bufo toad ===\n\n[[Bufo toad]] is found in the skin and glands of Bufo toads.<ref name=\":2\" /> It is commonly used in West Indian and Chinese cultures.<ref name=\":2\" /> West Indian cultures use it as an aphrodisiac called \u2018Love Stone\u2019.<ref name=\":2\" /> Chinese cultures use Bufo toad as heart medication called ''Chan su''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Research shows that it can have a negative effect on heart rate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Yohimbine ===\n[[File:Yohimbine structure.svg|thumb|upright=0.75|Yohimbine chemical structure]]\n\nYohimbine is a substance found in the bark of yohim trees in West Africa and, therefore, plant-based.<ref name=\":3\" /> It was traditionally used in West African cultures, in which the bark would be boiled and the resulting water drunk until its effects showed proven benefits in increasing sexual desire.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is now approved by the Food and Drug Administration and can be prescribed for sexual dysfunction in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> It is also found in over-the-counter health products.<ref name=\":0\" /> The chemical structure of yohimbine is an indole alkaloid that contains an adrenergic receptor blocker.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This blocker affects the central nervous system, autonomic nervous system, and penile tissue and vascular smooth muscle cells that help men with physiological issues and treats psychogenic erectile dysfunction.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Known side effects include nausea, anxiety, irregular heartbeats, and restlessness.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Horny goat weed  ===\n\n[[Horny goat weed]] (''Epimedii herba'') is found in a group of flowering plants used in Chinese folk medicine.<ref name=\":0\" /> Its intended use was to treat medical conditions and improve sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior.<ref name=\":0\" /> The chemical structure of horny goat weed consists of icariin, a flavanol glycoside.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Icariin has been shown to improve hormone regulation along with other benefits.<ref name=\":0\" /> Animal studies show a positive correlation to aphrodisiac qualities, but further research is needed to know the effects on humans.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Alcohol and marijuana===\n{{See also|Cannabis and sex}}\n[[File:Alcohol.png|upright=0.75|thumb|right|Alcohol Molecule]]\n\n[[Alcohol]] has been associated as an aphrodisiac due to its effect as a central nervous system depressant.<ref name=\":4\" /> Depressants can increase sexual desire and sexual behavior through disinhibition.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Alcohol affects people both physiologically and psychologically, and is therefore difficult to determine exactly how people are experiencing its aphrodisiacal effects (i.e., aphrodisiac qualities or the expectancy effect).<ref name=\":1\" /> Alcohol taken in moderate quantities can elicit a positive increase in sexual desire whereas larger quantities are associated with difficulties reaching sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chronic alcohol consumption is related to sexual dysfunction.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Marijuana]] reports are mixed with half of users claiming an increase in sexual desire and sexual pleasure while the other half reports no effect.<ref name=\":1\" /> Marijuana strain, consumption, and individual sensitivity&nbsp;are known factors that affect results.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Food ===\n[[File:Insam (ginseng).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Ginseng]]\nMany cultures have turned to food as a source of increasing sexual desire; however, significant research is lacking in the study of aphrodisiac qualities in food <ref name=\":1\" />. Most claims can be linked to the placebo effect aforementioned <ref name=\":1\" />. Misconceptions revolve around the visual appearance of these foods in relation to male and female genitalia (i.e., carrots, bananas, oysters, and the like) <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. Other beliefs arise from the thought of consuming animal genitals and absorbing their properties (i.e., cow cod soup in Jamaica or Ballut in the Philippines) <ref name=\":0\" />. The story of Aphrodite, who was born from the sea, is another reason why individuals believe seafood is another source of aphrodisiacs <ref name=\":4\" />. Foods that contain volatile oils have gained little recognition in their ability to improve sexual desire, sexual pleasure, and/or sexual behavior because they are irritants when released through the urinary tract <ref name=\":2\" />. Chocolate has been reported to increase sexual desire in women who consume it over those who do not <ref name=\":0\" />. Cloves and sage have been reported to demonstrate aphrodisiac qualities but their effects are\u00a0not yet specified <ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==== Ginseng ====\n\n[[Ginseng]] is found in Korea and is grouped in the Panaz family, known as Chinese ginseng.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The chemical structure of ginseng consists of ginsenosides and saponin glycosides.<ref name=\":3\" /> There are three different ways to process ginseng.<ref name=\":3\" /> Fresh ginseng is cut at four years of growth, white ginseng is cut at four to six years of growth, and red ginseng is cut, dried, and steamed at six years of growth.<ref name=\":3\" />&nbsp; Red ginseng has been reported to be the most effective aphrodisiac of the three.<ref name=\":3\" /> Known side effects include mild gastrointestinal upset.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Synthetic ===\n{{See also|Sex and drugs}}\n[[File:MDMA (simple).svg|upright=0.75|thumb|right|Ecstasy Molecule]] \nPopular party substances have been reported by users to consist of aphrodisiac properties because of their enhancing effects with sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n[[Ecstasy (drug)|Ecstasy]] users have reported an increase in sexual desire and sexual pleasure; however, there have been reports of delays in orgasm in both sexes and erectile difficulties in men.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Poppers]], an inhalant, have been linked to increased sexual pleasure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Known side effects are headaches, nausea, and temporary erectile difficulties.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Phenethylamines ====\n\n[[Amphetamine]] and [[methamphetamine]] are [[substituted phenethylamine|phenethylamine derivatives]] which are known to increase libido and cause frequent or prolonged erections as potential side effects, particularly at high [[wikt:supratherapeutic|supratherapeutic]] doses where sexual hyperexcitability and hypersexuality can occur;<ref name=\"Human amph effects\">{{cite book | author=Gunne LM | title=Drug Addiction II: Amphetamine, Psychotogen, and Marihuana Dependence | date=2013 | publisher=Springer | location=Berlin, Germany; Heidelberg, Germany | isbn=9783642667091 | pages=247\u2013260 | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gb_uCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA247#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate=4 December 2015 | chapter=Effects of Amphetamines in Humans }}</ref><ref name=\"FDA Effects\">{{cite web | title = Adderall XR Prescribing Information | url = http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2013/021303s026lbl.pdf | pages = 4&ndash;8 | work = United States Food and Drug Administration |date=December 2013 | accessdate = 30 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Libido\">{{cite journal | author = Montgomery KA | title = Sexual desire disorders | journal = Psychiatry (Edgmont) | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = 50&ndash;55 |date=June 2008 | pmid = 19727285 | pmc = 2695750 | doi = }}</ref><ref name=\"Desoxyn\">{{cite web| title=Desoxyn Prescribing Information| url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2013/005378s028lbl.pdf|date=December 2013 |work=United States Food and Drug Administration| accessdate=6 January 2014 | quote = ADVERSE REACTIONS&nbsp;... '''changes in libido'''; frequent or prolonged erections. [emphasis added]}}</ref> however, in some individuals who use these drugs, libido is reduced.<ref name=\"FDA Effects\" /><ref name=\"Desoxyn\" />\n\n==== Testosterone ====\n[[Libido]] in males is linked to levels of sex hormones, particularly [[testosterone]].<ref name=drugs/><ref>{{cite journal |title=The effects of testosterone on the cavernous tissue and erectile function |author=R. Shabsigh| year=1997|journal=World J. Urol.| pmid=9066090 | volume = 15 | pages = 21\u20136 | doi = 10.1007/BF01275152 |issue=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fisher|first=Helen E.|last2=Aron|first2=Arthur|last3=Brown|first3=Lucy L.|date=2006-12-29|title=Romantic love: a mammalian brain system for mate choice|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=361|issue=1476|pages=2173\u20132186|doi=10.1098/rstb.2006.1938|issn=0962-8436|pmid=17118931|pmc=1764845}}</ref> When a reduced sex drive occurs in individuals with relatively low levels of testosterone, particularly in [[postmenopausal]] women or men over age 60,<ref name=\"snyder\">{{cite journal|pmc=5209754|year=2016|last1=Snyder|first1=P. J|title=Effects of Testosterone Treatment in Older Men|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=374|issue=7|pages=611\u2013624|last2=Bhasin|first2=S|last3=Cunningham|first3=G. R|last4=Matsumoto|first4=A. M|last5=Stephens-Shields|first5=A. J|last6=Cauley|first6=J. A|last7=Gill|first7=T. M|last8=Barrett-Connor|first8=E|last9=Swerdloff|first9=R. S|last10=Wang|first10=C|last11=Ensrud|first11=K. E|last12=Lewis|first12=C. E|last13=Farrar|first13=J. T|last14=Cella|first14=D|last15=Rosen|first15=R. C|last16=Pahor|first16=M|last17=Crandall|first17=J. P|last18=Molitch|first18=M. E|last19=Cifelli|first19=D|last20=Dougar|first20=D|last21=Fluharty|first21=L|last22=Resnick|first22=S. M|last23=Storer|first23=T. W|last24=Anton|first24=S|last25=Basaria|first25=S|last26=Diem|first26=S. J|last27=Hou|first27=X|last28=Mohler Er|first28=I. I. I|last29=Parsons|first29=J. K|last30=Wenger|first30=N. K|display-authors=29|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1506119|pmid=26886521}}</ref> [[dietary supplement]]s that are purported to increase [[blood serum|serum]] testosterone concentrations have been used with intent to increase libido, although with limited benefit.<ref name=drugs/><ref name=snyder/> Long-term therapy with synthetic oral testosterone is associated with increased risk of [[cardiovascular diseases]].<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=4245724|year=2014|last1=Borst|first1=S. E|title=Cardiovascular risks and elevation of serum DHT vary by route of testosterone administration: A systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMC Medicine|volume=12|pages=211|last2=Shuster|first2=J. J|last3=Zou|first3=B|last4=Ye|first4=F|last5=Jia|first5=H|last6=Wokhlu|first6=A|last7=Yarrow|first7=J. F|doi=10.1186/s12916-014-0211-5|pmid=25428524}}</ref>\n\n== Risks ==\nSolid evidence is hard to obtain as these substances come from many different environments cross-culturally and therefore affect results due to variations in its growth and extraction.<ref name=\":3\" /> The same is also true for unnatural substances as variations in consumption and individual sensitivity can affect results.<ref name=\":1\" /> Folk medicine and self-prescribed methods can be potentially harmful as side effects are not fully known and therefore are not made aware to the people searching this topic on the internet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Popular culture==\n[[File:1926WantQuickPep.jpg|thumb|right|230px|An advertisement for pills from 1926 implies an aphrodisiac effect: \"full of red-blooded vim and push\".]]\n\nThe invention of an aphrodisiac is the basis of a number of films including [[Perfume: The Story of a Murderer (film)|''Perfume: The Story of a Murderer'']], ''[[Spanish Fly (1975 film)|Spanish Fly]]'', ''[[She'll Follow You Anywhere]]'', ''[[Love Potion No. 9 (film)|Love Potion No. 9]]'' and ''[[A Serbian Film]]''.  The first segment of [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask) (film)|Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask)]]'' is called \"Do Aphrodisiacs Work?\", and casts Allen as a [[court jester]] trying to seduce the [[Queen regnant|queen]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Anaphrodisiac]]\n* [[Food and sexuality]]\n* ''[[Fork Me, Spoon Me]]'', 2006 book\n* [[https://turkishaphrodisiacs.com]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Gabriele Frob\u00f6se, Rolf Frob\u00f6se, Michael Gross (Translator): ''Lust and Love: Is it more than Chemistry?'' Royal Society of Chemistry, 2006; {{ISBN|0-85404-867-7}}.\n* Michael Scott: \"Pillow Talk: A Comprehensive Guide to Erotic Hypnosis and Relyfe Programming\" Blue Deck Press, 2011; {{ISBN|0-98341-640-0}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aphrodisiacs}}\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/27752 ''Aphrodisiacs and Anti-aphrodisiacs: Three Essays on the Powers of Reproduction'' by John Davenport].\n\n{{-}}\n{{Aphrodisiacs}}\n\n{{Author